This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it presents a new method for label ranking using random forest, which is a popular machine learning algorithm. It may also belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as label ranking is often used in information retrieval tasks. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of random decision trees, which are commonly used in the sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also presents experimental results on datasets with partial ranking information, which suggests it may belong to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision) where partial ranking is often encountered. Finally, the paper's focus on aggregation strategies may suggest it belongs to the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
